Refacor Game

1. Extract the "last action" state into a dedicated struct
You have ~8 fields just for tracking the last action for animations/notifications:


lastAction, lastMovedWarriorID, lastStolenFrom, lastStolenCard,
lastSpyInfo, lastAttackWeaponID, lastAttackTargetID, lastAttackTargetPlayer
These will only grow with new card types. Extract them into an ActionResult or TurnEvent struct:


type ActionResult struct {
    Action            string
    MovedWarriorID    string
    StolenFrom        string
    StolenCard        ports.Card
    SpyInfo           string
    AttackWeaponID    string
    AttackTargetID    string
    AttackTargetPlayer string
    // future card types just add fields here
}
Game gets a single lastResult ActionResult field, and you reset it at the start of each action. This also makes it easier for GameStatusProvider to consume.

2. Command Pattern for game actions
This is the big one. Each action method in gameactions.go follows the same structure: validate turn/phase, get player/cards, execute, record result, call nextAction. As you add card types, this file will keep growing.

Instead, define actions as standalone types:


type GameAction interface {
    Validate(g *Game) error
    Execute(g *Game) (*ActionResult, error)
    Phase() types.ActionType  // which phase this belongs to
}

// Example
type AttackAction struct {
    PlayerName       string
    TargetPlayerName string
    TargetID         string
    WeaponID         string
}

func (a *AttackAction) Phase() types.ActionType { return types.Attack }

func (a *AttackAction) Validate(g *Game) error {
    // turn validation, player lookup, card type checks
}

func (a *AttackAction) Execute(g *Game) (*ActionResult, error) {
    // the actual attack logic
}
Then Game gets one generic method:


func (g *Game) ExecuteAction(action GameAction) (GameStatus, error) {
    if err := action.Validate(g); err != nil {
        return GameStatus{}, err
    }
    result, err := action.Execute(g)
    if err != nil {
        return GameStatus{}, err
    }
    g.lastResult = *result
    g.nextAction(action.Phase(), nil)
    return g.GameStatusProvider.Get(g.CurrentPlayer(), g), nil
}
Benefits:

New card types = new files with their action struct, not more methods on Game
Each action is independently testable
Game stays as the orchestrator, not the implementor
The handler layer (handlers.go) maps message types to action structs instead of calling different Game methods
3. Group remaining fields by concern
The win-condition fields (gameOver, winner, winnerIdx) and turn-tracking fields (hasMovedWarrior, hasTraded, CanMoveWarrior, CanTrade) could each be small structs:


type TurnState struct {
    CanMoveWarrior  bool
    HasMovedWarrior bool
    CanTrade        bool
    HasTraded       bool
    StartedAt       time.Time
}
This is lower priority but keeps the Game struct readable as it grows.

What I'd prioritize
ActionResult struct - Quick win, minimal refactor, immediate clarity
Command pattern - Higher effort but directly solves the "more card types = bigger Game" problem
Field grouping - Nice-to-have, do it as you touch those areas
The command pattern is the most impactful. It turns Game from "the thing that does everything" into "the thing that validates turns and dispatches actions" — which is what it's conceptually already doing, just not structurally.

Want me to plan the implementation for any of these?

